Function.Name: Buffered
Function.Description: Buffers the last accessed pixel block(s).

AnyType.Help: Local relief modelling removes the large scale morphological elements (hills, alleys…) from data so only small scale features remain (e.g. archaeology). This version of the tool uses a simplified process – the trend is computed by a simple mean filter and a trend removed model is produced directly by subtracting the filtered model from the original.

Argument.Name: Openness
Argument.Description: RVT Openness Positive/Negative. Calculates positive or negative opnenness.
Argument.Help: Openness is also a proxy for diffuse illumination and is based on an estimation of a mean horizon elevation angle within a defined search radius. The mean value of all zenith angles gives positive openness, while the mean nadir value gives negative openness. Positive openness is similar to skyview factor, with a more ‘flattened feel’, while negative openness gives additional information on convex features (Yokoyama et al. 2002). Because it is direction and shading independent and removes general topography, it is useful for automatic feature recognition.

AnyType.Name: Normalize
Slope
AnyType.Help: Slope gradient represents the maximum rate of change between each cell and its neighbours and can be calculated either as degree of slope or as percentage of slope. If presented in an inverted greyscale (steep slopes are darker), slope everity retains a very plastic representation of morphology (Doneus and Briese 2006). However, additional information is needed to distinguish between positive/convex (e.g. banks) and negative/concave (e.g. ditches) features since slopes of the same gradient (regardless of rising or falling) are presented with the same colour. The method requires no parameters.
